<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="436" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="24.[159,772,1278,2019]" box="[159,262,1278,1304]" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis box="[159,262,1278,1304]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[159,772,1278,2019]" lastBlockId="24.[816,1429,223,519]" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">
This is a brown, medium-sized 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kaup" authorityYear="1829" box="[594,674,1312,1338]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[594,674,1312,1338]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">Myotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (FA = 
<quantity box="[236,414,1346,1372]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.845" metricValueMax="3.88" metricValueMin="3.81" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" unit="mm" value="38.45" valueMax="38.8" valueMin="38.1">38.1–38.8 mm</quantity>
). One bat was captured flying low over rivers of 
<quantity box="[373,432,1380,1406]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" unit="m" value="10.0">10 m</quantity>
in width, surrounded by coffee plantations, and at an elevation less than 
<quantity box="[708,771,1414,1440]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" unit="m" value="50.0">50 m</quantity>
a.s.l. An adult male was collected by previous researchers from Gimbar 2 cave in Way Canguk Forest (MZB 35805). The wing membrane narrows markedly near the ankle and forms a prolonged strip inserting to the metatarsus, which has been seen in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1901" box="[159,272,1618,1644]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simus">
<emphasis box="[159,272,1618,1644]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">M. simus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[357,466,1618,1644]" name="Paraguay" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
(López-González 
<emphasis box="[698,764,1618,1644]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">et al.</emphasis>
, 2001) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kaup" authorityYear="1829" box="[291,371,1652,1678]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[291,371,1652,1678]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">Myotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp.1 from 
<collectingCountry box="[507,593,1652,1678]" name="Taiwan" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Huang" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Huang" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" refId="ref26238" refString="HUANG, C. - C., L. - L. LEE, and H. - C. KUO. 2008. An illustrated key to two middle size Myotis bats, Myotis taiwanensis and" type="book" year="2008">
Huang 
<emphasis box="[702,764,1652,1678]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">et al.</emphasis>
, 2008
</bibRefCitation>
). P 
<superScript attach="left" box="[261,271,1682,1700]" fontSize="8" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">3</superScript>
partially intrudes from the toothrow, and P 
<superScript attach="left" box="[175,185,1716,1734]" fontSize="8" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">2</superScript>
and P 
<superScript attach="left" box="[260,270,1716,1734]" fontSize="8" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">4</superScript>
are completely separated. The crown area of P 
<superScript attach="left" box="[210,220,1750,1768]" fontSize="8" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">3</superScript>
is around one-third that of P 
<superScript attach="left" box="[577,587,1750,1768]" fontSize="8" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">2</superScript>
and the crown area of P 
<subScript attach="left" box="[286,296,1803,1821]" fontSize="8" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">3</subScript>
around half that of P 
<subScript attach="right" box="[602,612,1803,1821]" fontSize="8" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">2</subScript>
. Comparing with known species on the Sunda Shelf, the bat is similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horsfield" baseAuthorityYear="1824" box="[307,450,1856,1882]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="adversus">
<emphasis box="[307,450,1856,1882]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">M. adversus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[466,604,1856,1882]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hasseltii">
<emphasis box="[466,604,1856,1882]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">M. hasseltii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="horsfieldii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">M. horsfieldii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in body size and habitat use (
<bibRefCitation author="Kingston" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Kingston" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" refId="ref26934" refString="KINGSTON, T., B. L. LIM, and A. ZUBAID. 2006. Bats of Krau Wildlife Reserve. Penerbit Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia, Bangi, 145 pp." type="book" year="2006">
Kingston 
<emphasis box="[704,764,1890,1916]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">et al.</emphasis>
, 2006
</bibRefCitation>
). However, the wing membranes attach directly to the ankle in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horsfield" baseAuthorityYear="1824" box="[428,571,1959,1985]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="adversus">
<emphasis box="[428,571,1959,1985]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">M. adversus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[627,764,1959,1985]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hasseltii">
<emphasis box="[627,764,1959,1985]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">M. hasseltii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and directly to the metatarsus in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[601,771,1993,2019]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="horsfieldii">
<emphasis box="[601,771,1993,2019]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">M. horsfieldii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="BATES, P. J. J. &amp; D. L. HARRISON" bookContentInfo="258 pp." box="[824,1156,223,249]" journalOrPublisher="Harrison Institute Museum Publications, Sevenoaks" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" refId="ref25042" refString="BATES, P. J. J., and D. L. HARRISON. 1997. Bats of the Indian Subcontinent. Harrison Institute Museum Publications, Sevenoaks, xv + 258 pp." title="Bats of the Indian Subcontinent" type="book" year="1997">Bates and Harrison, 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bates" box="[1178,1417,223,249]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Bates" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" pagination="205 - 236" refId="ref24627" refString="BATES, P. J. J., TIN NWE, SI SI HLA BU, KHIN MIE MIE, KHIN MAUNG SWE, NYO NYO, AYE AYE KHAING, NU NU AYE, YIN YIN TOKE, NAING NAING AUNG, et al. 2005. A review of the genera Myotis, Ia, Pipistrellus, Hypsugo, and Arielulus (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) from Myanmar (Burma), including three species new to the country. Acta Chiropterologica, 7: 205 - 236." type="journal article" year="2005">
Bates 
<emphasis box="[1260,1329,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">et al.</emphasis>
, 2005
</bibRefCitation>
). Moreover, P 
<superScript attach="left" box="[966,976,252,270]" fontSize="8" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">2</superScript>
is completely in line with the toothrow in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horsfield" baseAuthorityYear="1824" box="[925,1086,290,316]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="adversus">
<emphasis box="[925,1086,290,316]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">M. adversus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and displaced inward in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[816,958,324,350]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hasseltii">
<emphasis box="[816,958,324,350]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">M. hasseltii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Yasuma" box="[978,1230,324,350]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Yasuma" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" refId="ref29128" refString="YASUMA, S., M. AADAU, L. APIN, F. T. Y. YA, and L. KIMSUI. 2003. Identification Keys to the Mammals of Borneo. Sabah Parks and JICA, Kota Kinabalu, 85 pp." type="book" year="2003">
Yasuma 
<emphasis box="[1085,1149,324,350]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="436">et al.</emphasis>
, 2003
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Francis" box="[1247,1417,324,350]" firstAuthor="Francis" pageId="24" pageNumber="436" refId="ref25558" refString="FRANCIS, C. M. 2008. A guide to mammals of Southeast Asia. Princeton University Press, Princeton, NJ, 392 pp." type="book" year="2008">Francis, 2008</bibRefCitation>
). Based on the traits compared, we are not able to assign it to any known species. Genetic analyses and comparisons with more species across a greater geographic range are necessary for species identification.
</paragraph>
